english:
  title: A Record Inscribed on the Wall of the Hall of Attendants at the Uiheung Three Armies Bureau
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fifth year since the founding of Chosŏn, the Prince commanded the Uiheung Three Armies Bureau, saying: "From ancient times, those who govern a nation must make the employment of capable people their first priority. How much more so now, in this time of new beginnings? Though we gather worthy individuals from far and wide to manage our affairs, we fear that many talented people remain hidden and unrecognized. Let the officers and gentlemen of your bureau, along with other suitable men, submit the names of their sons, brothers, nephews, grandsons, and sons-in-law for recommendation. Place them in the Hall of Attendants to study the arts of both civil learning and martial skill. When their talents mature, promote them according to their abilities, overlooking none, and instruct them consistently so they may aid my governance and never fall into disuse."

    Thus were gathered several hundred young men from families of long-standing rank. The following spring, the Hall of Attendants was formally established at the bureau, and six masters of instruction were appointed to oversee separate fields of study. The School of Classical Learning was called the Hall of Understanding Principles and Applying Them; Military Science, the Hall of Calculation and Victory; Law, the Hall of Compassion and Care; Mathematics, the Hall of Clarity and Precision; Medicine was called the Art of Saving Life, and Archery, the Practice of Virtue. All the sons and daughters of noble and common officials alike, from age fifteen and upward, residing in the capital and not yet in office, were enrolled.

    Some questioned: "Are not there already schools for the sons of gentlemen? The Five Regional Schools and the State Academy? And do not Military Science, Law, Medicine, and Mathematics each have their own institutions? Is not the Hall of Attendants therefore redundant?"

    I respectfully examined the systems of Zhou. The Great Minister of the People held responsibility for teaching all people through six virtues, six practices, and six arts, thereby cultivating capable individuals as worthy guests. When a worthy man of talent appeared, the township would first recognize the most excellent and send him to the Minister of People. The Minister would then examine him further and advance him to the academy. The Grand Master of Music would examine him again and advance him to the office of the Military Chancellor—these were called "presented scholars." The Military Chancellor would examine their merit, report it in writing to the king, who would receive it with double obeisance, enter it into the Celestial Record, and only after thorough deliberation of office and talent would rank be conferred and stipend granted. Such was the care taken in selecting worthy men.

    Moreover, the Palace Master supervised the gentlemen and common folk of the royal household. All who appeared in the registers—whether born of legitimate line or collateral branches—including descendants of meritorious ministers and families of enduring virtue, were included. They were taught in both conduct and arts to serve the court's security, so that none but virtuous people attended the king and served in his retinue.

    Now your young people learn in their respective schools while young, and when grown, shall rise to office and thence to the Three Armies Bureau. This bureau represents the ancient office of the Military Chancellor. Teaching conduct and arts while maintaining security, examining each person's talents before granting rank—through this system no worthy talent need languish unknown, and the path of undeserved advancement is closed. This is but the enduring wisdom of Zhou's governance.

    In antiquity, the civil and martial were not two separate paths. In times of peace, people were nurtured through rites, music, and moral education, studying principles to enlighten their understanding and perfect their virtue. In times of crisis, they were applied in formation and ranks, arousing courage and spirit to accomplish great deeds. Thus the moral instruction of yesterday became the noble conduct of tomorrow. Such people could draw near to the ruler and shape his virtue, could care for the common people and secure their welfare, could maintain the integrity of the guard and the strength of defense—all grounded in the power of learning.

    In the three ancient dynasties, accomplished individuals were complete in both capacities—their civil learning unified the multitude, their martial prowess awed the enemy, as the saying goes: "Those with both civil and martial virtue become models for all lands."

    When later ages saw this teaching decline, people cultivated only what came naturally. Scholars became pedantic and narrow; warriors became arrogant and fierce. Seeking those who could serve the people, we find them often weak in defense; seeking those who could repel invasion, we find them often lacking in protection. This is because their daily practice confined them to a single path, preventing them from achieving integration.

    But now, when scholars study within a military bureau, and armored soldiers hear lessons of learning and virtue, through mutual influence and gradual refinement, correcting the imbalance of nature and perfecting their capabilities, such outstanding talent must surely emerge. The flourishing of worthy people and the elevation of governance will bring no shame when compared to antiquity.

    I humbly reflect that our Prince, endowed with brilliant and martial virtue, has founded the dynasty and established its lineage. The Duke of Fenghua, Jeong Do-jeon, with his benevolent heart and profound learning, has aided him in creating our nation's institutions. All that is established follows the systems of Zhou, and our foundational order is grand and enduring—one may judge all else by this.

    The Duke commanded me to inscribe these words upon this hall's wall, to illuminate the Prince's quest for worthy talent and his virtue in nurturing capable people for ages to come. Though I possess limited skill, I dare not refuse. I have briefly recorded how today's work accords with Zhou's ancient design, and offer it as this inscription.
